235–1294","1260–1319":"1260–1319","–1294":"–1294","–1303":"–1303","–Female":"Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1205–1242":"1205–1242","1204–Female":"1204–Overleden","1242":"1242","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","May 1242":"mei 1242","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1303":"1303","1225":"1225","about 1239":"circa 1239","by 1268  1st wife":"januari 1268","1235":"1235","1234":"1234","1319":"1319","Kenardington, Kent, England":"Kenardington, Kent, England","Adlingfleet, Yorkshire, England":"Adlingfleet, Yorkshire, England","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1239–1290":"about 1239–1290","1225–1281":"1225–1281","1234–1282":"1234–1282","1239–1290":"1239–1290","1235–1294":"1235–1294","1260–1319":"1260–1319","–1294":"–1294","–1303":"–1303","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1205–1242":"1205–1242","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1242":"1242","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","May 1242":"May 1242","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1303":"1303","1225":"1225","about 1239":"about 1239","by 1268  1st wife":"January 1268","1235":"1235","1234":"1234","1319":"1319","Kenardington, Kent, England":"Kenardington, Kent, England","Adlingfleet, Yorkshire, England":"Adlingfleet, Yorkshire, England","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Eiville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Staffordshire):","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Déville in Seine-Maritime.","nickname from Middle English <i>devel</i> ‘devil’ (Old English <i>dēofol</i>). This may have been acquired as a pageant name or as a shortened form of a longer nickname such as that of Robert and William <i>Drepedevel</i> (‘kill the devil’), recorded in the 1301 Subsidy Rolls (Sutton Howgrave, in Kirklington, North Yorkshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Davoll","meanings":["English: variant of   Deaville  ."]},{"name":"Dewell","meanings":["English:","variant of   Deaville  , a nickname from Middle English <i>devel</i> (Old English <i>dēofol</i>) ‘devil, Satan’, possibly acquired as a pageant name or as a shortened form of a longer nickname. Compare   Devall   and   Deeble  .","of Breton origin, a variant of   Joel   from the Old Breton personal name <i>Iudhael</i>. The personal name was seemingly reintroduced into Britain from France in the 17th century by Huguenots, and was common in Devon and Cornwall and the Breton districts of Yorkshire and the eastern counties."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret d'Eiville was born about 1239, in Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Robert Daiville, was 35 and her mother, Mrs. Robert de Eiville, was 36. She married John Lovetot the Elder in January 1268. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters. She died in 1290, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1239–1290":"umbes 1239–1290","1225–1281":"1225–1281","1234–1282":"1234–1282","1239–1290":"1239–1290","1235–1294":"1235–1294","1260–1319":"1260–1319","–1294":"–1294","–1303":"–1303","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1205–1242":"1205–1242","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1242":"1242","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","May 1242":"mai 1242","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1303":"1303","1225":"1225","about 1239":"umbes 1239","by 1268  1st wife":"jaanuar 1268","1235":"1235","1234":"1234","1319":"1319","Kenardington, Kent, England":"Kenardington, Kent, England","Adlingfleet, Yorkshire, England":"